Deployment flow:
            Developer push
                 |
                 v
            GitHub Actions
              - lint
              - test
              - build
              - scan
                 |
                 v
            Commit image/tag or config change
                 |
                 v
            GitOps repo updated
                 |
                 v
            Argo CD detects diff
                 |
                 v
            Sync to cluster
                 |
                 v
            Kubernetes rollout
                 |
                 v
            Readiness / health checks
                 |
                 v
            Smoke tests / observability checks
==================================================================================================================
GitHub Actions workflow:
      A typical workflow file is placed in .github/workflows/ 
      and contains jobs and steps that GitHub runs on repository 
      events such as push or pull request creation.
            name: ci-cd
            on:
              push:
                branches: [main]
              pull_request:
            
            jobs:
              lint-test:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                steps:
                  - uses: actions/checkout@v5
                  - run: make lint
                  - run: make test
            
              build:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                needs: lint-test
                steps:
                  - uses: actions/checkout@v5
                  - run: make build
            
              deploy-dev:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                needs: build
                steps:
                  - uses: actions/checkout@v5
                  - run: make argocd-sync-myapp-dev
==================================================================================================================

CI stage table:
| Stage  | Purpose                  | Typical YAML/parameter                               |
| ------ | ------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| Lint   | Static checks            | workflow job + steps: run: make lint docs.github+1   |
| Test   | Unit/integration checks  | needs can enforce order hsf-training.github+1        |
| Build  | Image/package creation   | build job with checkout and build step               |
| Scan   | Security checks          | dedicated job or step after build                    |
| Deploy | Sync or apply to cluster | make argocd-sync-* or Helm release                   |
| Verify | Readiness and health     | kubectl get pods, argocd app get                     |

Operations runbook:
            1) Confirm desired state
            Check the application state with Argo CD and Kubernetes.
            
            Verify whether the issue is sync, health, or rollout related.
            
            Compare the active values file to the intended environment file.
            
            2) Validate YAML
            Check indentation, key names, and file path.
            
            Confirm the right values file is wired into Helm or Argo CD.
            
            Ensure secrets, ConfigMaps, and dashboard names match exactly.
            
            3) Check cluster objects
            Inspect pods, deployments, StatefulSets, DaemonSets, jobs, and PVCs.
            
            Look for Pending, CrashLoopBackOff, ImagePullBackOff, or missing ConfigMap/Secret events.
            
            Verify quotas, namespace labels, and network policies if resources fail to schedule.
            
            4) Check logs and events
            Use pod logs for crash details.
            
            Check describe pod events for mount, webhook, or scheduling failures.
            
            For Argo CD issues, inspect controller or server behavior and app status.
            
            5) Sync or roll back
            For GitOps: fix Git, commit, and let Argo CD reconcile.
            
            For immediate mitigation: delete the bad pod, restart a workload, or revert to a known-good revision.
            
            Keep rollback Git-first; use Kubernetes rollback only as emergency recovery.
            
            6) Re-verify
            Confirm pods are Running and Ready.
==================================================================================================================
            
            Confirm dashboards, alerts, and logs are visible.
            
            Confirm app health becomes Healthy and sync becomes Synced.


